{"title_page": "Per Nielsen", "text_new": "{{About||the Danish musician and trumpet player|Per Nielsen (musician)|the Danish Olympic shooter|Per Nielsen (sport shooter)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Per Nielsen\n| image= Per Nielsen JM 0286.jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| fullname = Per Lundgren Nielsen\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1973|10|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[\u00c5rhus]], Denmark\n| height = 1.91 m\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = 1979\u20131993\n| youthclubs1 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]\n| years1 = 1993\u20132008\n| clubs1 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]<ref name=\"df\"/>\n| caps1 = 394\n| goals1 = 23\n| nationalyears1 = 1993\n| nationalteam1 = [[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U-19]]<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/>\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1994\u20131996\n| nationalteam2 = [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Denmark U-21]]<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/>\n| nationalcaps2 = 19\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 2002\u20132006\n| nationalteam3 = [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/>\n| nationalcaps3 = 10\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2008\u20132010\n| managerclubs1 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] (youth)\n| manageryears2 = 2011\u20132014\n| managerclubs2 = [[Hvidovre IF]]\n| manageryears3 = 2015\u2013\n| managerclubs3 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF (women)]]\n}}\n'''Per Lundgren Nielsen'''<ref name=\"haslund\"/> ({{IPA-da|\u02c8p\u02b0\u025b\u0250\u032f \u02c8ne\u031dlsn\u0329}}; born 15 October 1973) is a Danish former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played in the [[defender (association football)|central defense]] of [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] in the [[Danish Superliga]] for his entire club career. With Br\u00f8ndby, Nielsen won five [[Danish football champions|Danish championships]] and three [[Danish Cup]]s since his senior debut in 1993. He played 547 official games for Br\u00f8ndby IF and scored 26 goals, and from 2002 to 2008 he was named [[Captain (association football)|team captain]]. He played 10 matches for the [[Denmark national football team]] and is noted for 19 matches for the [[Denmark national under-21 football team|national under-21 team]] from 1994 to 1996. Following his retirement, he has worked as first as an assistant coach, later as head coach. Since 2015 he has been coaching Br\u00f8ndby's women's team.\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[\u00c5rhus]],<ref name=\"haslund\">[http://www.haslund.info/danmark/as/nieper.asp Per Nielsen] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101013044722/http://www.haslund.info/danmark/as/nieper.asp |date=13 October 2010 }} at Haslund.info</ref> Nielsen's parents moved to [[Br\u00f8ndby]] when he was a child, and he enrolled at Br\u00f8ndby IF at the age of five.<ref name=\"br\u00f8ndby\">{{in lang|da}} [http://www.brondby.com/player.asp?sid=7&id=33 Br\u00f8ndby IF profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128145151/http://www.brondby.com/player.asp?sid=7&id=33 |date=28 November 2006 }}</ref> Nielsen made his senior debut in the Br\u00f8ndby IF jersey on 26 June 1993,<ref name=\"br\u00f8ndby\"/> and debuted in the [[Danish Superliga]] championship in March 1995.<ref name=\"df\"/> Nielsen was touted as the long-term successor of central defender [[Uche Okechukwu]] and was permanently moved into the senior squad in December 1993, coming from a Br\u00f8ndby youth team that sported several later first team regulars, including [[Kim Daugaard]], [[Allan Ravn]] and later [[Denmark national football team|Danish national team]] player [[Ebbe Sand]].<ref>Kurt Stendal, \"Br\u00f8ndbys unge garde\", ''[[Berlingske Tidende]]'', 6 December 1993.</ref>\n\nNielsen became a mainstay in the team during the [[1995\u201396 Danish Superliga|1995\u201396 Superliga]] season,<ref name=\"df\">[http://www.danskfodbold.com/spiller.php?spillerid=10109&ligaid=2001 Per Lundgren Nielsen] at DanskFodbold.com</ref> as Br\u00f8ndby won the Danish championship, and established himself as a regular starter. He helped Br\u00f8ndby repeat the Superliga win in the [[1996\u201397 Danish Superliga|1996\u201397 Superliga]] and [[Double (association football)|the Double]] of both Superliga championship and [[Danish Cup]] title in 1998. Following the [[2001\u201302 Danish Superliga|2001\u201302 Superliga]] championship triumph with Br\u00f8ndby, Danish international [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] [[Mogens Krogh]] retired, and Nielsen was chosen as new [[Captain (association football)|team captain]]. After his second Danish Cup triumph in 2003, Nielsen was elected the 2003 Br\u00f8ndby IF ''Player of the Year''.<ref name=\"playeroftheyear\">[http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=33492 \u00c5rets Spiller] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709091818/http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=33492 |date=9 July 2010 }} at [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the Danish football players' association announced a [[strike action]]. Br\u00f8ndby was still in European competition, and would be forced to field a team consisting of retired Br\u00f8ndby professionals, youth team players and recent signings who had yet to become members of the players' association, in the August 2004 [[UEFA Cup]] qualification re-match against [[FK Ventspils]]. Two days before the match, Nielsen and team mate [[Dan Anton Johansen]] broke the strike and returned to the Br\u00f8ndby training,<ref>{{in lang|da}} [http://www.brondby.com/article.asp?aid=33698 Br\u00f8ndby IF \u2013 2004], [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]], 4 January 2005.</ref> causing a lot of controversy in the process. The day after, the players' and football clubs' associations reached a provisorical agreement,<ref>{{in lang|da}} [http://www.danskmetal.dk/sw18806.asp?usepf=true OK04: Spillerkonflikt afbl\u00e6st] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050225191956/http://danskmetal.dk/sw18806.asp?usepf=true |date=25 February 2005 }}, [[Dansk Metal]] 25 August 2004.</ref> and Br\u00f8ndby's first team players were selected for the match, though they were eliminated on aggregate.\n\nHe captained Br\u00f8ndby to the Double of the [[2004\u201305 Danish Superliga|2004\u201305 Superliga]] and Danish Cup titles, and was named 2006 Br\u00f8ndby IF ''Player of the Year''.<ref name=\"playeroftheyear\"/> In February 2008, Nielsen chose to resign from the position of [[Captain (association football)|team captain]], stating that he would spend his remaining one and a half years at Br\u00f8ndby helping the club move on, also if that meant him taking a place on the bench.<ref>{{in lang|da}} [http://www.brondby.com/article.asp?aid=45940 Per Nielsen overdrager anf\u00f8rerhvervet], Br\u00f8ndby IF, 22 February 2008.</ref> [[Stef\u00e1n G\u00edslason]] was named his successor. Nielsen helped Br\u00f8ndby win the 2008 Danish Cup, his last trophy with the team. Nielsen announced that he would retire as an active footballer in late June 2008. Instead he will continue as a scout in Br\u00f8ndby. His last game in the blue and yellow jersey was his [[testimonial match]] against Spanish team [[Deportivo La Coruna]] on 12 July 2008.<ref>[http://www.brondby.com/article.asp?aid=47510&id=5 Per Nielsen testimonial mod La Coruna], Br\u00f8ndby IF, 27 June 2008.</ref> Nielsen played a total 547 games in all competitions,<ref>[http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=32438 1. holdsspillere i Br\u00f8ndby IF] at [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]</ref> including 394 games and scored 23 goals for Br\u00f8ndby in the Superliga.<ref name=\"df\"/>\n\n==Coaching career==\nFollowing three years Brondby IF youth coach, he spent four years as Hvidovre IF head coach. In 2015, he took over as coach for Danish women's champions [[Brondby IF (women)|Brondby IF]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.uefa.com/womenschampionsleague/news/newsid=2200630.html | title=Nielsen succeeds Lisdorf as Br\u00f8ndby coach | publisher=uefa.com | date=30 December 2014 | accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> In april 2019 Per Nielsen prolonged his contract with [[Brondby IF (women)|Brondby IF]] so that he would stay with the team until 2021.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://3point.dk/per-nielsen-forlaenger-med-broendby-women/ | title=Per Nielsen forl\u00e6nger med Br\u00f8ndby Women | publisher=3point.dk | date=15 April 2019 | accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> The team won the championship in 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://3point.dk/per-nielsen-efter-mesterskab-det-bliver-jeg-aldrig-traet-af/ | title=Per Nielsen efter mesterskab: Det bliver jeg aldrig tr\u00e6t af | publisher=3point.dk | date=9 May 2019 | accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nNielsen's first international game was a single [[Denmark national under-19 football team|under-19 national team]] match in December 1993.<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/> He was called up to play for the [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Danish national under-21 team]] in March 1994, and went on to play 19 games and score two goals for the under-21 national team until July 1996.<ref name=\"dbuofficial\">[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/2319&allmatch=1#match Per Nielsen \u2013 Alle hold (Alle kampe)] at [[Danish Football Association]]</ref>\n\nDespite winning several trophies with Br\u00f8ndby, Nielsen never broke into the Danish national team, but he was selected to play for the league national team, consisting of the best players from the domestic Danish Superliga championship. He went on his first trip with the league national team in 1997, playing three games at the [[US Cup]] in [[California]], United States.<ref name=\"dbuunofficial\">[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/2319&teamtypeid=2165&off=0#match Per Nielsen \u2013 Ligalandshold (Alle uofficielle kampe)] at [[Danish Football Association]]</ref> He likewise took part in the league national team campaign in Colombia, Ecuador and Venezuela in 1999,<ref name=\"dbuunofficial\"/> with injuries forcing him out of the 1998 tour. Nielsen was once again included in the Danish league national team's trip to California in 2004, where he made his 10th and last appearance for the team,<ref name=\"dbuunofficial\"/> with injuries forcing him out of the 2003 tour. In January 2006, Nielsen was called up for his sixth trip with the Danish league national team. However, he chose not to travel with the team to the [[Carlsberg Cup]] in [[Hong Kong]], citing personal reasons, which national team coach [[Morten Olsen]] fully supported.<ref>{{in lang|da}} [http://www.dbu.dk/news/newsShow.aspx?id=41183 Ligalandsholds-afbud fra Per Nielsen], [[Danish Football Association|DBU]], 5 January 2006.</ref>\n\nNielsen finally debuted for the Danish national team in September 2002 as a late substitute,<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/> and he would go on to be among the fringe players of the Danish squad. He played a total 10 national team games until November 2006, helping Denmark qualify for the [[2004 UEFA European Football Championship|2004 European Championship]].<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Player===\n* [[Danish Superliga]]: [[1995\u201396 Danish Superliga|1995\u201396]], [[1996\u201397 Danish Superliga|1996\u201397]], [[1997\u201398 Danish Superliga|1997\u201398]], [[2001\u201302 Danish Superliga|2001\u201302]], [[2004\u201305 Danish Superliga|2004\u201305]]\n* [[Danish Cup]]: [[1997\u201398 Danish Cup|1997\u201398]], [[2002\u201303 Danish Cup|2002\u201303]], [[2004\u201305 Danish Cup|2004\u201305]], [[2007\u201308 Danish Cup|2007\u201308]]\n* Br\u00f8ndby IF ''Player of the Year'': 2003, 2006\n\n===Manager===\n* [[Elitedivisionen|Danish Women League]]: 2015, 2017, 2019\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/2319 Danish national team profile]\n*{{in lang|da}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20061128145151/http://www.brondby.com/player.asp?sid=7&id=33 Br\u00f8ndby IF profile]\n\n{{Br\u00f8ndby IF Player of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nielsen, Per}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish footballers]]\n[[Category:Br\u00f8ndby IF players]]\n[[Category:Denmark international footballers]]\n[[Category:Denmark under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:People from Aarhus]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football players who received a testimonial]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the Danish musician and trumpet player|Per Nielsen (musician)|the Danish Olympic shooter|Per Nielsen (sport shooter)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Per Nielsen\n| image= Per Nielsen JM 0286.jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| fullname = Per Lundgren Nielsen\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1973|10|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[\u00c5rhus]], Denmark\n| height = 1.91 m\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = 1979\u20131993\n| youthclubs1 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]\n| years1 = 1993\u20132008\n| clubs1 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]<ref name=\"df\"/>\n| caps1 = 394\n| goals1 = 23\n| nationalyears1 = 1993\n| nationalteam1 = [[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U-19]]<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/>\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1994\u20131996\n| nationalteam2 = [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Denmark U-21]]<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/>\n| nationalcaps2 = 19\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 2002\u20132006\n| nationalteam3 = [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/>\n| nationalcaps3 = 10\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2008\u20132010\n| managerclubs1 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] (youth)\n| manageryears2 = 2011\u20132014\n| managerclubs2 = [[Hvidovre IF]]\n| manageryears3 = 2015\u2013\n| managerclubs3 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF (women)]]\n}}\n'''Per Lundgren Nielsen'''<ref name=\"haslund\"/> ({{IPA-da|\u02c8p\u02b0\u025b\u0250\u032f \u02c8nelsn\u0329}}; born 15 October 1973) is a Danish former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played in the [[defender (association football)|central defense]] of [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] in the [[Danish Superliga]] for his entire club career. With Br\u00f8ndby, Nielsen won five [[Danish football champions|Danish championships]] and three [[Danish Cup]]s since his senior debut in 1993. He played 547 official games for Br\u00f8ndby IF and scored 26 goals, and from 2002 to 2008 he was named [[Captain (association football)|team captain]]. He played 10 matches for the [[Denmark national football team]] and is noted for 19 matches for the [[Denmark national under-21 football team|national under-21 team]] from 1994 to 1996. Following his retirement, he has worked as first as an assistant coach, later as head coach. Since 2015 he has been coaching Br\u00f8ndby's women's team.\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[\u00c5rhus]],<ref name=\"haslund\">[http://www.haslund.info/danmark/as/nieper.asp Per Nielsen] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101013044722/http://www.haslund.info/danmark/as/nieper.asp |date=13 October 2010 }} at Haslund.info</ref> Nielsen's parents moved to [[Br\u00f8ndby]] when he was a child, and he enrolled at Br\u00f8ndby IF at the age of five.<ref name=\"br\u00f8ndby\">{{in lang|da}} [http://www.brondby.com/player.asp?sid=7&id=33 Br\u00f8ndby IF profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128145151/http://www.brondby.com/player.asp?sid=7&id=33 |date=28 November 2006 }}</ref> Nielsen made his senior debut in the Br\u00f8ndby IF jersey on 26 June 1993,<ref name=\"br\u00f8ndby\"/> and debuted in the [[Danish Superliga]] championship in March 1995.<ref name=\"df\"/> Nielsen was touted as the long-term successor of central defender [[Uche Okechukwu]] and was permanently moved into the senior squad in December 1993, coming from a Br\u00f8ndby youth team that sported several later first team regulars, including [[Kim Daugaard]], [[Allan Ravn]] and later [[Denmark national football team|Danish national team]] player [[Ebbe Sand]].<ref>Kurt Stendal, \"Br\u00f8ndbys unge garde\", ''[[Berlingske Tidende]]'', 6 December 1993.</ref>\n\nNielsen became a mainstay in the team during the [[1995\u201396 Danish Superliga|1995\u201396 Superliga]] season,<ref name=\"df\">[http://www.danskfodbold.com/spiller.php?spillerid=10109&ligaid=2001 Per Lundgren Nielsen] at DanskFodbold.com</ref> as Br\u00f8ndby won the Danish championship, and established himself as a regular starter. He helped Br\u00f8ndby repeat the Superliga win in the [[1996\u201397 Danish Superliga|1996\u201397 Superliga]] and [[Double (association football)|the Double]] of both Superliga championship and [[Danish Cup]] title in 1998. Following the [[2001\u201302 Danish Superliga|2001\u201302 Superliga]] championship triumph with Br\u00f8ndby, Danish international [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] [[Mogens Krogh]] retired, and Nielsen was chosen as new [[Captain (association football)|team captain]]. After his second Danish Cup triumph in 2003, Nielsen was elected the 2003 Br\u00f8ndby IF ''Player of the Year''.<ref name=\"playeroftheyear\">[http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=33492 \u00c5rets Spiller] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709091818/http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=33492 |date=9 July 2010 }} at [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the Danish football players' association announced a [[strike action]]. Br\u00f8ndby was still in European competition, and would be forced to field a team consisting of retired Br\u00f8ndby professionals, youth team players and recent signings who had yet to become members of the players' association, in the August 2004 [[UEFA Cup]] qualification re-match against [[FK Ventspils]]. Two days before the match, Nielsen and team mate [[Dan Anton Johansen]] broke the strike and returned to the Br\u00f8ndby training,<ref>{{in lang|da}} [http://www.brondby.com/article.asp?aid=33698 Br\u00f8ndby IF \u2013 2004], [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]], 4 January 2005.</ref> causing a lot of controversy in the process. The day after, the players' and football clubs' associations reached a provisorical agreement,<ref>{{in lang|da}} [http://www.danskmetal.dk/sw18806.asp?usepf=true OK04: Spillerkonflikt afbl\u00e6st] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050225191956/http://danskmetal.dk/sw18806.asp?usepf=true |date=25 February 2005 }}, [[Dansk Metal]] 25 August 2004.</ref> and Br\u00f8ndby's first team players were selected for the match, though they were eliminated on aggregate.\n\nHe captained Br\u00f8ndby to the Double of the [[2004\u201305 Danish Superliga|2004\u201305 Superliga]] and Danish Cup titles, and was named 2006 Br\u00f8ndby IF ''Player of the Year''.<ref name=\"playeroftheyear\"/> In February 2008, Nielsen chose to resign from the position of [[Captain (association football)|team captain]], stating that he would spend his remaining one and a half years at Br\u00f8ndby helping the club move on, also if that meant him taking a place on the bench.<ref>{{in lang|da}} [http://www.brondby.com/article.asp?aid=45940 Per Nielsen overdrager anf\u00f8rerhvervet], Br\u00f8ndby IF, 22 February 2008.</ref> [[Stef\u00e1n G\u00edslason]] was named his successor. Nielsen helped Br\u00f8ndby win the 2008 Danish Cup, his last trophy with the team. Nielsen announced that he would retire as an active footballer in late June 2008. Instead he will continue as a scout in Br\u00f8ndby. His last game in the blue and yellow jersey was his [[testimonial match]] against Spanish team [[Deportivo La Coruna]] on 12 July 2008.<ref>[http://www.brondby.com/article.asp?aid=47510&id=5 Per Nielsen testimonial mod La Coruna], Br\u00f8ndby IF, 27 June 2008.</ref> Nielsen played a total 547 games in all competitions,<ref>[http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=32438 1. holdsspillere i Br\u00f8ndby IF] at [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]</ref> including 394 games and scored 23 goals for Br\u00f8ndby in the Superliga.<ref name=\"df\"/>\n\n==Coaching career==\nFollowing three years Brondby IF youth coach, he spent four years as Hvidovre IF head coach. In 2015, he took over as coach for Danish women's champions [[Brondby IF (women)|Brondby IF]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.uefa.com/womenschampionsleague/news/newsid=2200630.html | title=Nielsen succeeds Lisdorf as Br\u00f8ndby coach | publisher=uefa.com | date=30 December 2014 | accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> In april 2019 Per Nielsen prolonged his contract with [[Brondby IF (women)|Brondby IF]] so that he would stay with the team until 2021.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://3point.dk/per-nielsen-forlaenger-med-broendby-women/ | title=Per Nielsen forl\u00e6nger med Br\u00f8ndby Women | publisher=3point.dk | date=15 April 2019 | accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> The team won the championship in 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://3point.dk/per-nielsen-efter-mesterskab-det-bliver-jeg-aldrig-traet-af/ | title=Per Nielsen efter mesterskab: Det bliver jeg aldrig tr\u00e6t af | publisher=3point.dk | date=9 May 2019 | accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nNielsen's first international game was a single [[Denmark national under-19 football team|under-19 national team]] match in December 1993.<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/> He was called up to play for the [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Danish national under-21 team]] in March 1994, and went on to play 19 games and score two goals for the under-21 national team until July 1996.<ref name=\"dbuofficial\">[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/2319&allmatch=1#match Per Nielsen \u2013 Alle hold (Alle kampe)] at [[Danish Football Association]]</ref>\n\nDespite winning several trophies with Br\u00f8ndby, Nielsen never broke into the Danish national team, but he was selected to play for the league national team, consisting of the best players from the domestic Danish Superliga championship. He went on his first trip with the league national team in 1997, playing three games at the [[US Cup]] in [[California]], United States.<ref name=\"dbuunofficial\">[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/2319&teamtypeid=2165&off=0#match Per Nielsen \u2013 Ligalandshold (Alle uofficielle kampe)] at [[Danish Football Association]]</ref> He likewise took part in the league national team campaign in Colombia, Ecuador and Venezuela in 1999,<ref name=\"dbuunofficial\"/> with injuries forcing him out of the 1998 tour. Nielsen was once again included in the Danish league national team's trip to California in 2004, where he made his 10th and last appearance for the team,<ref name=\"dbuunofficial\"/> with injuries forcing him out of the 2003 tour. In January 2006, Nielsen was called up for his sixth trip with the Danish league national team. However, he chose not to travel with the team to the [[Carlsberg Cup]] in [[Hong Kong]], citing personal reasons, which national team coach [[Morten Olsen]] fully supported.<ref>{{in lang|da}} [http://www.dbu.dk/news/newsShow.aspx?id=41183 Ligalandsholds-afbud fra Per Nielsen], [[Danish Football Association|DBU]], 5 January 2006.</ref>\n\nNielsen finally debuted for the Danish national team in September 2002 as a late substitute,<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/> and he would go on to be among the fringe players of the Danish squad. He played a total 10 national team games until November 2006, helping Denmark qualify for the [[2004 UEFA European Football Championship|2004 European Championship]].<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Player===\n* [[Danish Superliga]]: [[1995\u201396 Danish Superliga|1995\u201396]], [[1996\u201397 Danish Superliga|1996\u201397]], [[1997\u201398 Danish Superliga|1997\u201398]], [[2001\u201302 Danish Superliga|2001\u201302]], [[2004\u201305 Danish Superliga|2004\u201305]]\n* [[Danish Cup]]: [[1997\u201398 Danish Cup|1997\u201398]], [[2002\u201303 Danish Cup|2002\u201303]], [[2004\u201305 Danish Cup|2004\u201305]], [[2007\u201308 Danish Cup|2007\u201308]]\n* Br\u00f8ndby IF ''Player of the Year'': 2003, 2006\n\n===Manager===\n* [[Elitedivisionen|Danish Women League]]: 2015, 2017, 2019\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/2319 Danish national team profile]\n*{{in lang|da}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20061128145151/http://www.brondby.com/player.asp?sid=7&id=33 Br\u00f8ndby IF profile]\n\n{{Br\u00f8ndby IF Player of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nielsen, Per}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish footballers]]\n[[Category:Br\u00f8ndby IF players]]\n[[Category:Denmark international footballers]]\n[[Category:Denmark under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:People from Aarhus]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football players who received a testimonial]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingDanish IPA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Per_Nielsen"}
{"title_page": "Tivolisaga (Original Swedish Cast Recording)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Tivolisaga (Original Swedish Cast Recording)\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Johan Christher Sch\u00fctz]], Johan Pettersson\n| cover      = Tivolisaga Original Cast Recording album cover.jpg\n| alt        = \n| released   = 2018\n| recorded   = \n| venue      = [[Arbisteatern]]\n| studio     = One Perfect Line Music\n| genre      = [[Musical theatre]], [[pop music|Pop]], [[rock music|Rock]], [[World music]]\n| length     = 52:01\n| label      = One Perfect Line Music\n| producer   = [[Johan Christher Sch\u00fctz]]\n| prev_title = [[Beautiful Place]]\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title = [[Bull Rider Boy]]\n| next_year  = 2019\n}}\n\n'''''Tivolisaga (Original Swedish Cast Recording)''''' is a musical theatre [[cast recording]] of the [[Sweden|Swedish]] musical ''Tivolisaga'' (\"''Carnival Tale''\"), by [[Johan Christher Sch\u00fctz]] and Johan Pettersson based on [[Romeo and Juliet]] by [[William Shakespeare]]. The album was released on 17 December 2018 by One Perfect Line Music.<ref>Official biography: http://www.johanchristherschutz.net/press/jcschutz-formal-bio.pdf</ref>\n\nAll songs have lyrics by Sch\u00fctz and music by Sch\u00fctz and Pettersson, and were originally written in 1997-1998 for their band ''Punch and Judy Show'', and in the musical, the characters Romeo and Juliet have been renamed [[Punch and Judy]].<ref>Cast Recording page on official website: http://www.tivolisaga.com/castrecording.php</ref> The music is inspired by pop, rock, tango, rumba and Swedish folk music.<ref>Spotify page: http://open.spotify.com/album/0S19vz4mVGWJTYfppXfm5s</ref>\n\nThe album was [[Music Producer|produced]] by Sch\u00fctz in his One Perfect Line Music studios, and features Linn\u00e9a K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m and Olle Petersson in the lead roles as Judy and Punch, [[Mathias Blad]] as Tempest, and Christian Zell as the Priest. Sch\u00fctz and Pettersson also make brief [[cameo appearance]]s.<ref>Album page on Sch\u00fctz's official website: http://www.johanchristherschutz.net/discography.php?do=view&id=201802&title=Tivolisaga%20-%20Original%20Swedish%20Cast%20Recording</ref>\n\nAfter the release, K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m and Petersson were invited to perform two of the songs live in Swedish radio, along with Johan Petersson; Sch\u00fctz was not able to participate.<ref>Swedish Broadcasting Corporation (Sveriges Radio) F\u00f6rmiddag i P4 \u00d6sterg\u00f6tland, Friday 1 March, 2019: https://sverigesradio.se/avsnitt/1245602</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Actor\n! Character\n|-\n\n|-\n| Linn\u00e9a K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m\n| Judy\n|-\n| Olle Petersson\n| Punch\n|-\n| Christian Zell\n| The Priest\n|-\n| [[Mathias Blad]]\n| Tempest\n|-\n| Louice Ottosson\n| Marilyn\n|-\n| Frippe Pettersson\n| The Mayor, Judy's father\n|-\n| Elin G\u00e5rdfalk\n| Rosetta\n|-\n| Karl Sanner\n| Antilles\n|-\n| Johan Wahlstr\u00f6m\n| Valentine\n|-\n| Valeria Valdes\n| Johanna (Siamese twin)\n|-\n| Kajsa Nilsson\n| Paulina (Siamese twin)\n|-\n| [[Johan Christher Sch\u00fctz]]\n| Proteus\n|-\n| Johan Pettersson\n| Carnival Director\n|-\n|}\n\n==Track listing==\n# Ouvertyr\n# Shakespeare Street\n# Bli n\u00e5nting stort\n# Min v\u00e4rld ligger ljus\u00e5r fr\u00e5n din\n# Statyer\n# Min v\u00e4rld ligger ljus\u00e5r fr\u00e5n din (Repris 1)\n# Tvillingpiruett\n# Jag kommer ingenstans\n# Min v\u00e4rld ligger ljus\u00e5r fr\u00e5n din (Repris 2)\n# Vilken lycka\n# \u00c4r det r\u00e4tt?\n# Ett \u00f6gonblick till\n# Hela v\u00e4rlden snurrar\n# Bli n\u00e5nting stort (Repris)\n# Ge mig ett tecken\n# Br\u00e5ktango\n# Marilyn\n# S\u00f6mnl\u00f6s\n# Snart g\u00e5r solen upp\n# Final - Leva sitt liv\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.tivolisaga.com Official website\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tivolisaga}}\n[[Category:J. C. Sch\u00fctz albums]]\n[[Category:2018 albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Tivolisaga (Original Swedish Cast Recording)\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Johan Christher Sch\u00fctz]], Johan Pettersson\n| cover      = Tivolisaga Original Cast Recording album cover.jpg\n| alt        = \n| released   = 2018\n| recorded   = \n| venue      = [[Arbisteatern]]\n| studio     = One Perfect Line Music\n| genre      = [[Musical theatre]], [[pop music|Pop]], [[rock music|Rock]], [[World music]]\n| length     = 52:01\n| label      = One Perfect Line Music\n| producer   = [[Johan Christher Sch\u00fctz]]\n| prev_title = [[Beautiful Place]]\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title = [[Bull Rider Boy]]\n| next_year  = 2019\n}}\n\n'''''Tivolisaga (Original Swedish Cast Recording)''''' is a musical theatre [[cast recording]] of the [[Sweden|Swedish]] musical ''Tivolisaga'' (\"''Carnival Tale''\"), by [[Johan Christher Sch\u00fctz]] and Johan Pettersson based on [[Romeo and Juliet]] by [[William Shakespeare]]. The album was released on 17 December 2018 by One Perfect Line Music.<ref>Official biography: http://www.johanchristherschutz.net/press/jcschutz-formal-bio.pdf</ref>\n\nAll songs have lyrics by Sch\u00fctz and music by Sch\u00fctz and Pettersson, and were originally written in 1997-1998 for their band ''Punch and Judy Show'', and in the musical, the characters Romeo and Juliet have been renamed [[Punch and Judy]].<ref>Cast Recording page on official website: http://www.tivolisaga.com/castrecording.php</ref> The music is inspired by pop, rock, tango, rumba and Swedish folk music.<ref>Spotify page: http://open.spotify.com/album/0S19vz4mVGWJTYfppXfm5s</ref>\n\nThe album was [[Music Producer|produced]] by Sch\u00fctz in his One Perfect Line Music studios, and features Linn\u00e9a K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m and Olle Petersson in the lead roles as Judy and Punch, [[Mathias Blad]] as Tempest, and Christian Zell as the Priest. Sch\u00fctz and Pettersson also participate in small [[Cameo appearance]]s.<ref>Album page on Sch\u00fctz's official website: http://www.johanchristherschutz.net/discography.php?do=view&id=201802&title=Tivolisaga%20-%20Original%20Swedish%20Cast%20Recording</ref>\n\nAfter the release, K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m and Petersson were invited to perform two of the songs live in Swedish radio, along with Johan Petersson; Sch\u00fctz was not able to participate.<ref>Swedish Broadcasting Corporation (Sveriges Radio) F\u00f6rmiddag i P4 \u00d6sterg\u00f6tland, Friday 1 March, 2019: https://sverigesradio.se/avsnitt/1245602</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Actor\n! Character\n|-\n\n|-\n| Linn\u00e9a K\u00e4llstr\u00f6m\n| Judy\n|-\n| Olle Petersson\n| Punch\n|-\n| Christian Zell\n| The Priest\n|-\n| [[Mathias Blad]]\n| Tempest\n|-\n| Louice Ottosson\n| Marilyn\n|-\n| Frippe Pettersson\n| The Mayor, Judy's father\n|-\n| Elin G\u00e5rdfalk\n| Rosetta\n|-\n| Karl Sanner\n| Antilles\n|-\n| Johan Wahlstr\u00f6m\n| Valentine\n|-\n| Valeria Valdes\n| Johanna (Siamese twin)\n|-\n| Kajsa Nilsson\n| Paulina (Siamese twin)\n|-\n| [[Johan Christher Sch\u00fctz]]\n| Proteus\n|-\n| Johan Pettersson\n| Carnival Director\n|-\n|}\n\n==Track listing==\n# Ouvertyr\n# Shakespeare Street\n# Bli n\u00e5nting stort\n# Min v\u00e4rld ligger ljus\u00e5r fr\u00e5n din\n# Statyer\n# Min v\u00e4rld ligger ljus\u00e5r fr\u00e5n din (Repris 1)\n# Tvillingpiruett\n# Jag kommer ingenstans\n# Min v\u00e4rld ligger ljus\u00e5r fr\u00e5n din (Repris 2)\n# Vilken lycka\n# \u00c4r det r\u00e4tt?\n# Ett \u00f6gonblick till\n# Hela v\u00e4rlden snurrar\n# Bli n\u00e5nting stort (Repris)\n# Ge mig ett tecken\n# Br\u00e5ktango\n# Marilyn\n# S\u00f6mnl\u00f6s\n# Snart g\u00e5r solen upp\n# Final - Leva sitt liv\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.tivolisaga.com Official website\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tivolisaga}}\n[[Category:J. C. Sch\u00fctz albums]]\n[[Category:2018 albums]]\n", "name_user": "LeaPoetree", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tivolisaga_(Original_Swedish_