ails/fridaynightlight00biss}}\n* {{cite book | last = Davis | first = Parke H. | title = Football, the American intercollegiate game | publisher=Nabu Press | year = 2010 | isbn = 978-1-171-91212-5}}\n* {{cite book| last = Fox | first = Stephen | title = Big Leagues: Professional Baseball, Football, and Basketball in National Memory | publisher = University of Nebraska Press | year = 1998 | isbn = 0-688-09300-0 | url = https://archive.org/details/bigleagues00step}}\n* {{cite book | last = MacCambridge | first = Michael (''Ed.'') | title = ESPN College Football Encyclopedia: The Complete History of the Game | publisher=Hyperion Books\n|year = 2005 | location = New York | isbn = 1-4013-3703-1}}\n* {{cite book| last = Perrin | first = Tom | title = Football: A College History | publisher = McFarland & Co Inc | year = 1987 | isbn = 0-89950-294-6 | url = https://archive.org/details/footballcollegeh00perr}}\n* {{cite book | last = Smith | first = Ronald A. | title = Sports and Freedom: The Rise of Big-Time College Athletics | url = https://archive.org/details/sportsfreedomris0000smit | url-access = registration | publisher=Oxford University Press | year = 1988 | isbn = 0-19-506582-4}}\n* {{cite book | last = Watterson | first = John Sayle | title = College Football: History, Spectacle, Controversy | url = https://archive.org/details/collegefootballh0000watt | url-access = registration | publisher=The Johns Hopkins University Press | location = Baltimore, Maryland | year = 2000 | isbn = 0-8018-6428-3}}\n* {{cite book| last = Whittingham | first = Richard | title = Sunday's Heroes | publisher = Triumph Books | location = Chicago | year = 2003 | isbn = 1-57243-517-8 | url = https://archive.org/details/sundaysheroesnfl0000whit_x2j5}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.football-almanac.com/ Football Almanac]\n* [http://www.profootballresearchers.org/ Professional Football Researchers Association]\n* [https://footballfoundation.org/ National Football Foundation]\n* [http://www.collegefootball.org/ College Football Hall of Fame]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151016182814/http://profootballhof.org/ Pro Football Hall of Fame]\n\n{{Featured article}}\n{{American football concepts}}\n{{American football in the United States}}\n{{Football codes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of American Football}}\n[[Category:History of American football| ]]\n", "name_user": "74.88.70.21", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_American_football"}
{"title_page": "Mariann Fischer Boel", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2009}}\n{{Weasel|date=October 2011}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name           = Mariann Fischer Boel\n|image          = File:Mariann Fischer Boel.jpg\n|office         = [[European Commissioner for Agriculture and Rural Development]]\n|president      = [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]]\n|term_start     = 22 November 2004\n|term_end       = 9 February 2010\n|predecessor    = [[Franz Fischler]]<br>[[Sandra Kalniete]] <small>(Agriculture, Rural Development and [[European Commissioner for Maritime Affairs and Fisheries|Fisheries]])</small>\n|successor      = [[Dacian Ciolo\u015f]]\n|office2        = [[List of Ministers for Food, Agriculture and Fisheries of Denmark|Minister for Food, Agriculture and Fisheries]]\n|primeminister2 = [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]]\n|term_start2    = 27 November 2001\n|term_end2      = 2 August 2004\n|predecessor2   = [[Ritt Bjerregaard]]\n|successor2     = [[Hans Christian Schmidt]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1943|4|15|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[\u00c5sum, Denmark|\u00c5sum]], Denmark\n|death_date     =\n|death_place    =\n|party          = [[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]]\n}}\n'''Mariann Fischer Boel''' ({{IPA-da|m\u0251\u0281i\u02c8\u00e6n \u02c8fi\u0255\u0250 \u02c8po\u02c0l}}; born 15 April 1943, [[\u00c5sum, Denmark|\u00c5sum]]) is a [[politics of Denmark|Danish politician]], serving as [[European Commission]]er for Agriculture and Rural Development from 2004 to 2009. A member of the party [[Left (Denmark)|Venstre]], she had previously been minister of agriculture and foods since 2002, in the government of [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]].\n\nIn 2008, she was given the European Taxpayers' Award from the Taxpayers' Association of Europe for her decision to abolish export refunds for exports of live cattle from the EU, and for her ongoing efforts to improve the transparency of agricultural payments.\n\nIn 2008, she was presented with the Danish European Movement's price for \"European of the Year\".\n\nIn 2008, she was awarded the Wine Personality of the Year 2008 award by the International Wine Challenge, which said, about her efforts to drag the European wine industry into the 21st century, that \"family vineyards might have been pulled up and the family winemaking tradition lost had it not been for the intrepid heroine from the north\".\n\n==General approach to the CAP==\n\nAs Commissioner, FIscher Boel has based her work on three guiding principles:\n*The [[Common Agricultural Policy]] (CAP) needed to take European farming towards still greater competitiveness and market-responsiveness by placing production decisions more firmly in the hands of farmers rather than administrators.\n*The CAP needed to address the needs of rural areas as a whole, not only those of agriculture.\n*In particular, the CAP needed to reflect growing concern about environmental issues, including [[climate change]].\n\nShe has continued the CAP reform process, notably within the three sectors that were exempted from the reform of 2003: sugar, fruit and vegetables, and wine. The sectors had initially been left alone partly because reforming them presented huge political difficulties.\n\nBoel also took steps to bolster the [[EU Rural Development Policy]], preparing it to deliver more coherent and balanced results against clear objectives in the new\nfinancial period of 2007 to 2013.\n\nLater in her mandate, she carried out a review of the CAP, which became known as the \u201cCAP Health Check\u201d and made further policy adjustments to ensure that the reformed CAP was working as intended and was addressing the challenges of the 21st century.\n\n==Sugar reform==\n\nWhen Boel took office in 2004, the EU had regulated its sugar sector in more or less\nthe same way for some 40 years, supporting a domestic sugar price far above world market prices to keep production in place in each country.\n\nAlthough the EU did not have a comparative advantage in sugar production, its policy was creating large surpluses that were exported with subsidies, which was not welcomed by many of its trade partners.\n\nWith Boel's reform, agreed in 2005, the benchmark EU sugar price was cut by 36 per cent over several years, which helped to bring the EU sugar industry back into a sustainable and more natural balance with the rest of the world market, as a net importer rather than exporter.\n\nBringing sugar beet farmers into the Single Payment Scheme gave them support which was in line with the need for competitiveness and which also depended on environmental standards (through crosscompliance). The reforms are also funding restructuring programmes in areas that sugar factories shut down, helping workers laid off to find new jobs and putting disused factory sites back into good environmental condition.\n\n==Fruit and vegetable reform==\n\nIn 2006, she proposed reforms to the fruit and vegetable sector, which was agreed in principle in June 2007. It gives extra incentives to producers to band together into \"producer organisations\", which can negotiate with retailers on a more equal footing.\nProducer organisations are now also in charge of managing market crises through disposal schemes and other methods, and they must spend a minimum share of their budget on care for the environment.\n\nAn aspect of the reform, very much inspired by emerging public needs, was the mandate to draw up a school fruit scheme to which the EU agreed in November 2008. It was launched in the 2009/2010 school year and operates in 22 EU countries. It provides funding to\ndistribute fruit and vegetables in schools as well as to support programmes to educate children, parents and teachers about healthy diets.\n\n==Wine reform==\nAs European Union agriculture commissioner, Boel has been a vocal advocate for various [[vine pull schemes]] in an attempt to compensate for the 1.7&nbsp;billion bottle [[wine surplus]] that Europe has had for the last several [[vintage]]s. Every year, the European Union spends 500&nbsp;million euros to [[distill]] the excess wine into [[industrial alcohol]].\n\nUnder the 2007 reform, subsidies for distilling unwanted wines are being phased out, and the money is being spent instead on a broad menu of measures to make the wine sector more competitive and to care for vine landscapes. In an important step to prepare for liberalisation, a three-year voluntary \"grubbing-up scheme\", with strong environmental safeguards, is offering money to uncompetitive producers who wish to dig up their vines and leave the sector.\n\nCritics have claimed that the implementation of Boel's plan will see a 5% drop in wine industry jobs and 7% decrease in wine prices by 2009, but most agree that the price of wine will eventually rise again. Supporters of Boel's plan have noted that European wine consumption has decreased an average of 0.65% a year and that in a few years, imports of [[New World wine]] into Europe will exceed European exports, which will also have negative effects on wine industry jobs and wine prices.<ref>M. Frank & D. Macle ''\"Europe's Plan to Pull Up Vines Decried... Again\"'', The Wine Spectator, p. 15, Sept. 30, 2007.</ref>\n\n==CAP health check==\n\nIn 2008, she carried out a review of the CAP, which was dubbed the \"CAP Health Check\". The package of adjustments was agreed to in November 2008, with the aim of keeping the CAP to the spirit of the 2003 reforms in the changing circumstances.\n\nUnder the health check, the EU's rural development policy was given a boost in order to help farms and other rural businesses respond to pressing challenges, such as fighting and adjusting to climate change, managing water more carefully, providing and using renewable energy, conserving biodiversity and pursuing innovation in all of these areas.\n\nIn order to finance the new projects, a key element of the Health Check agreement is that by 2012, EU farmers will be contributing an extra 5% of their income support payments to rural development policy (through modulation) for use in projects to help address the concerns listed above. A further 4% is being transferred annually from all income support payment amounts above a threshold of \u20ac300,000. That finally establishes a principle long supported by the public: farmers who receive high levels of income\nsupport from the EU budget should make larger \"contributions\" to projects of general public interest.\n\nTo make farming even more market-orientated, the Health Check is decoupling a greater share of farmers' income support payments.\n\nThe Health Check is also removing constraints on farmers\u2019 freedom to produce more in response to market demand. The requirement to set aside a portion of their arable land is abolished, and milk production quotas are being enlarged to prepare for their removal in 2015.\n\n==Increasing transparency, accountability and cutting red tape==\n\nDuring her five years in office, she introduced new rules, which have improved drastically transparency on CAP payments. Since April 2009, all member states have been required to maintain websites listing beneficiaries of CAP funding. For each beneficiary, the websites state the full name, the municipality and the value of funding received. The EU\u2019s EUROPA website contains links to these national websites.\n\nShe also succeeded in becoming the first agricultural commissioner to get the green light for the CAP spendings from the Court of Auditors, which means that 98% of all spendings were free of errors. She has also overseen a large amount of simplification projects, which have cut administrative burden and red tape in CAP. Most famously, she abolished marketing standards for 26 types of fruit and vegetable, which has led to the reintroduction of the curvy cucumber on supermarket shelves.\n\n==Helping the world to feed itself==\n\nIn 2008, she proposed to make available a so-called \"food facility\" worth \u20ac1&nbsp;billion over three years, which has given a much-needed boost to agricultural production in poorer countries, such as by helping farmers to access fertiliser and seed. It has also funded safety net systems to provide for the basic food needs of vulnerable people in these countries, including children.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://ec.europa.eu/commission_barroso/fischer-boel/index_en.htm }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070118115914/http://blogs.ec.europa.eu/fischer-boel Mariann Fischer Boel's blog]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Ritt Bjerregaard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Ministers for Food, Agriculture and Fisheries of Denmark|Minister for Food, Agriculture and Fisheries]]|years=2001\u20132004}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Hans Christian Schmidt]]}}\n|-\n{{S-bef|before=[[Poul Nielson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Danish European Commissioner]]|years=2004\u20132009}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Connie Hedegaard]]}}\n|-\n{{S-bef|before=[[Franz Fischler]]<br>[[Sandra Kalniete]]|as=European Commissioner for Agriculture, Rural Development and [[European Commissioner for Maritime Affairs and Fisheries|Fisheries]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[European Commissioner for Agriculture and Rural Development]]|years=2004\u20132009}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Dacian Ciolo\u015f]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{First Barroso Commission}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fischer Boel, Mariann}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish European Commissioners]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Members of the Folketing]]\n[[Category:Venstre (Denmark) politicians]]\n[[Category:Women European Commissioners]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Folketing]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2009}}\n{{Weasel|date=October 2011}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name           = Mariann Fischer Boel\n|image          = File:Mariann Fischer Boel.jpg\n|office         = [[European Commissioner for Agriculture and Rural Development]]\n|president      = [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]]\n|term_start     = 22 November 2004\n|term_end       = 9 February 2010\n|predecessor    = [[Franz Fischler]]<br>[[Sandra Kalniete]] <small>(Agriculture, Rural Development and [[European Commissioner for Maritime Affairs and Fisheries|Fisheries]])</small>\n|successor      = [[Dacian Ciolo\u015f]]\n|office2        = [[List of Ministers for Food, Agriculture and Fisheries of Denmark|Minister for Food, Agriculture and Fisheries]]\n|primeminister2 = [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]]\n|term_start2    = 27 November 2001\n|term_end2      = 2 August 2004\n|predecessor2   = [[Ritt Bjerregaard]]\n|successor2     = [[Hans Christian Schmidt]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1943|4|15|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[\u00c5sum, Denmark|\u00c5sum]], Denmark\n|death_date     =\n|death_place    =\n|party          = [[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]]\n}}\n'''Mariann Fischer Boel''' ({{IPA-da|ma\u0281i\u02c8\u00e6n \u02c8fi\u0255\u0250 \u02c8po\u02c0l}}; born 15 April 1943, [[\u00c5sum, Denmark|\u00c5sum]]) is a [[politics of Denmark|Danish politician]], serving as [[European Commission]]er for Agriculture and Rural Development from 2004 to 2009. A member of the party [[Left (Denmark)|Venstre]], she had previously been minister of agriculture and foods since 2002, in the government of [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]].\n\nIn 2008, she was given the European Taxpayers' Award from the Taxpayers' Association of Europe for her decision to abolish export refunds for exports of live cattle from the EU, and for her ongoing efforts to improve the transparency of agricultural payments.\n\nIn 2008, she was presented with the Danish European Movement's price for \"European of the Year\".\n\nIn 2008, she was awarded the Wine Personality of the Year 2008 award by the International Wine Challenge, which said, about her efforts to drag the European wine industry into the 21st century, that \"family vineyards might have been pulled up and the family winemaking tradition lost had it not been for the intrepid heroine from the north\".\n\n==General approach to the CAP==\n\nAs Commissioner, FIscher Boel has based her work on three guiding principles:\n*The [[Common Agricultural Policy]] (CAP) needed to take European farming towards still greater competitiveness and market-responsiveness by placing production decisions more firmly in the hands of farmers rather than administrators.\n*The CAP needed to address the needs of rural areas as a whole, not only those of agriculture.\n*In particular, the CAP needed to reflect growing concern about environmental issues, including [[climate change]].\n\nShe has continued the CAP reform process, notably within the three sectors that were exempted from the reform of 2003: sugar, fruit and vegetables, and wine. The sectors had initially been left alone partly because reforming them presented huge political difficulties.\n\nBoel also took steps to bolster the [[EU Rural Development Policy]], preparing it to deliver more coherent and balanced results against clear objectives in the new\nfinancial period of 2007 to 2013.\n\nLater in her mandate, she carried out a review of the CAP, which became known as the \u201cCAP Health Check\u201d and made further policy adjustments to ensure that the reformed CAP was working as intended and was addressing the challenges of the 21st century.\n\n==Sugar reform==\n\nWhen Boel took office in 2004, the EU had regulated its sugar sector in more or less\nthe same way for some 40 years, supporting a domestic sugar price far above world market prices to keep production in place in each country.\n\nAlthough the EU did not have a comparative advantage in sugar production, its policy was creating large surpluses that were exported with subsidies, which was not welcomed by many of its trade partners.\n\nWith Boel's reform, agreed in 2005, the benchmark EU sugar price was cut by 36 per cent over several years, which helped to bring the EU sugar industry back into a sustainable and more natural balance with the rest of the world market, as a net importer rather than exporter.\n\nBringing sugar beet farmers into the Single Payment Scheme gave them support which was in line with the need for competitiveness and which also depended on environmental standards (through crosscompliance). The reforms are also funding restructuring programmes in areas that sugar factories shut down, helping workers laid off to find new jobs and putting disused factory sites back into good environmental condition.\n\n==Fruit and vegetable reform==\n\nIn 2006, she proposed reforms to the fruit and vegetable sector, which was agreed in principle in June 2007. It gives extra incentives to producers to band together into \"producer organisations\", which can negotiate with retailers on a more equal footing.\nProducer organisations are now also in charge of managing market crises through disposal schemes and other methods, and they must spend a minimum share of their budget on care for the environment.\n\nAn aspect of the reform, very much inspired by emerging public needs, was the mandate to draw up a school fruit scheme to which the EU agreed in November 2008. It was launched in the 2009/2010 school year and operates in 22 EU countries. It provides funding to\ndistribute fruit and vegetables in schools as well as to support programmes to educate children, parents and teachers about healthy diets.\n\n==Wine reform==\nAs European Union agriculture commissioner, Boel has been a vocal advocate for various [[vine pull schemes]] in an attempt to compensate for the 1.7&nbsp;billion bottle [[wine surplus]] that Europe has had for the last several [[vintage]]s. Every year, the European Union spends 500&nbsp;million euros to [[distill]] the excess wine into [[industrial alcohol]].\n\nUnder the 2007 reform, subsidies for distilling unwanted wines are being phased out, and the money is being spent instead on a broad menu of measures to make the wine sector more competitive and to care for vine landscapes. In an important step to prepare for liberalisation, a three-year voluntary \"grubbing-up scheme\", with strong environmental safeguards, is offering money to uncompetitive producers who wish to dig up their vines and leave the sector.\n\nCritics have claimed that the implementation of Boel's plan will see a 5% drop in wine industry jobs and 7% decrease in wine prices by 2009, but most agree that the price of wine will eventually rise again. Supporters of Boel's plan have noted that European wine consumption has decreased an average of 0.65% a year and that in a few years, imports of [[New World wine]] into Europe will exceed European exports, which will also have negative effects on wine industry jobs and wine prices.<ref>M. Frank & D. Macle ''\"Europe's Plan to Pull Up Vines Decried... Again\"'', The Wine Spectator, p. 15, Sept. 30, 2007.</ref>\n\n==CAP health check==\n\nIn 2008, she carried out a review of the CAP, which was dubbed the \"CAP Health Check\". The package of adjustments was agreed to in November 2008, with the aim of keeping the CAP to the spirit of the 2003 reforms in the changing circumstances.\n\nUnder the health check, the EU's rural development policy was given a boost in order to help farms and other rural businesses respond to pressing challenges, such as fighting and adjusting to climate change, managing water more carefully, providing and using renewable energy, conserving biodiversity and pursuing innovation in all of these areas.\n\nIn order to finance the new projects, a key element of the Health Check agreement is that by 2012, EU farmers will be contributing an extra 5% of their income support payments to rural development policy (through modulation) for use in projects to help address the concerns listed above. A further 4% is being transferred annually from all income support payment amounts above a threshold of \u20ac300,000. That finally establishes a principle long supported by the public: farmers who receive high levels of income\nsupport from the EU budget should make larger \"contributions\" to projects of general public interest.\n\nTo make farming even more market-orientated, the Health Check is decoupling a greater share of farmers' income support payments.\n\nThe Health Check is also removing constraints on farmers\u2019 freedom to produce more in response to market demand. The requirement to set aside a portion of their arable land is abolished, and milk production quotas are being enlarged to prepare for their removal in 2015.\n\n==Increasing transparency, accountability and cutting red tape==\n\nDuring her five years in office, she introduced new rules, which have improved drastically transparency on CAP payments. Since April 2009, all member states have been required to maintain websites listing beneficiaries of CAP funding. For each beneficiary, the websites state the full name, the municipality and the value of funding received. The EU\u2019s EUROPA website contains links to these national websites.\n\nShe also succeeded in becoming the first agricultural commissioner to get the green light for the CAP spendings from the Court of Auditors, which means that 98% of all spendings were free of errors. She has also overseen a large amount of simplification projects, which have cut administrative burden and red tape in CAP. Most famously, she abolished marketing standards for 26 types of fruit and vegetable, which has led to the reintroduction of the curvy cucumber on supermarket shelves.\n\n==Helping the world to feed itself==\n\nIn 2008, she proposed to make available a so-called \"food facility\" worth \u20ac1&nbsp;billion over three years, which has given a much-needed boost to agricultural production in poorer countries, such as by helping farmers to access fertiliser and seed. It has also funded safety net systems to provide for the basic food needs of vulnerable people in these countries, including children.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://ec.europa.eu/commission_barroso/fischer-boel/index_en.htm }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070118115914/http://blogs.ec.europa.eu/fischer-boel Mariann Fischer Boel's blog]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Ritt Bjerregaard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Ministers for Food, Agriculture and Fisheries of Denmark|Minister for Food, Agriculture and Fisheries]]|years=2001\u20132004}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Hans Christian Schmidt]]}}\n|-\n{{S-bef|before=[[Poul Nielson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Danish European Commissioner]]|years=2004\u20132009}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Connie Hedegaard]]}}\n|-\n{{S-bef|before=[[Franz Fischler]]<br>[[Sandra Kalniete]]|as=European Commissioner for Agriculture, Rural Development and [[European Commissioner for Maritime Affairs and Fisheries|Fisheries]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[European Commissioner for Agriculture and Rural Development]]|years=2004\u20132009}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Dacian Ciolo\u015f]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{First Barroso Commission}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fischer Boel, Mariann}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish European Commissioners]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Members of the Folketing]]\n[[Category:Venstre (Denmark) politicians]]\n[[Category:Women European Commissioners]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Folketing]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingDanish IPA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mariann_Fischer_Boel"}
{"title_page": "March 15", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\nIn the [[Roman calendar]], March 15 was known as the [[Ides of March]].\n\n==Events==\n*[[474 BC]] &ndash; [[Roman consul]] [[Gnaeus Manlius Vulso (consul 474 BC)|Gnaeus Manlius Vulso]] celebrates an [[ovation]] for concluding the [[Roman\u2013Etruscan Wars#Veii-Sabine alliance 475-474 BC|war]] against [[Veii]] and securing a forty years' truce.<ref>''[[Fasti Triumphales]]''</ref> \n*[[44 BC]] &ndash; [[Marcus Junius Brutus the Younger]] and his fellow conspirators, [[Gaius Cassius Longinus]], [[Decimus Junius Brutus Albinus|Decimus Junius Brutus]], and several other [[Roman Senate|Roman senators]], march to the Capitol following the [[assassination of Julius Caesar]], but there is no response to their appeals to the population, who have left the streets in fear. Caesar's body remains in its place \n* [[351]] &ndash; [[Constantius II]] elevates his cousin [[Constantius Gallus|Gallus]] to [[Caesar (title)|Caesar]], and puts him in charge of the Eastern part of the [[Roman Empire]].\n* [[493]] &ndash; [[Odoacer]], the first barbarian [[King of Italy]] after the fall of the [[Western Roman Empire]], is slain by [[Theoderic the Great]], king of the [[Ostrogoths]], while the two kings were feasting together.\n* [[856]] &ndash; [[Michael III]], emperor of the [[Byzantine Empire]], overthrows the regency of his mother, empress [[Theodora (wife of Theophilos)|Theodora]] (wife of Theophilos) with support of the Byzantine [[nobility]].\n* [[933]] &ndash; After a ten-year truce, German King [[Henry the Fowler]] defeats a Hungarian army at the [[Battle of Riade]] near the [[Unstrut]] river.\n*[[1147]] &ndash; [[Conquest of Santar\u00e9m]]: The forces of [[Afonso I of Portugal]] capture [[Santar\u00e9m, Portugal|Santar\u00e9m]].\n*[[1311]] &ndash; [[Battle of Halmyros]]: The [[Catalan Company]] defeats [[Walter V, Count of Brienne]] to take control of the [[Duchy of Athens]], a [[Crusader states|Crusader state]] in Greece.\n*[[1493]] &ndash; [[Christopher Columbus]] returns to Spain after his first trip to the Americas.\n*[[1564]] &ndash; Mughal Emperor [[Akbar]] abolishes \"[[jizya]]\" (''per capita'' tax).\n*[[1672]] &ndash; [[Charles II of England]] issues the [[Royal Declaration of Indulgence]].\n*[[1781]] &ndash; [[American Revolutionary War]]: [[Battle of Guilford Court House]]: Near present-day [[Greensboro, North Carolina]], 1,900 British troops under General [[Charles Cornwallis]] defeat a mixed American force numbering 4,400 in a [[Pyrrhic victory]].\n*[[1783]] &ndash; In an emotional speech in [[Newburgh, New York]], [[George Washington]] asks his officers not to support the [[Newburgh Conspiracy]]. The plea is successful and the threatened [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] never takes place.\n*[[1819]] &ndash; French physicist [[Augustin-Jean Fresnel|Augustin Fresnel]] is adjudged the winner of the ''Grand Prix'' of the [[French Academy of Sciences|Acad\u00e9mie des Sciences]] for his \"Memoir on the Diffraction of Light\", which verifies the [[Fresnel integral]]s, accounts for the limited extent to which light spreads into shadows, and thereby demolishes [[Isaac Newton|Newton]]'s initial objection to the wave theory of light.\n*[[1820]] &ndash; [[Maine]] becomes the 23rd [[U.S. state]].\n*[[1827]] &ndash; [[University of Toronto]] is founded.\n*[[1848]] &ndash; A [[Hungarian Revolution of 1848|revolution breaks out in Hungary]]. The [[Habsburg]] rulers are compelled to meet the demands of the Reform party.\n*[[1864]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: The [[Red River Campaign]]: U.S. Navy fleet arrives at [[Alexandria, Louisiana]].\n*[[1874]] &ndash; [[French Third Republic|France]] and [[Nguy\u1ec5n dynasty|Vietnam]] sign the [[Second Treaty of Saigon]], further recognizing the full sovereignty of France over [[Cochinchina]].\n*[[1875]] &ndash; [[Archbishop of New York]] [[John McCloskey]] is named the first [[cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]] in the United States.\n*[[1877]] &ndash; [[First ever official cricket test match is played]]: Australia vs England at the [[MCG Stadium]], in [[Melbourne]], Australia.\n*[[1878]] &ndash; [[Restoration of the Scottish Catholic hierarchy]], broken off back in 1603.\n*[[1888]] &ndash; Start of the [[Sikkim Expedition|Anglo-Tibetan War of 1888]].\n*[[1895]] &ndash; [[Heian Shrine]] is founded.\n*[[1906]] &ndash; [[Rolls-Royce Limited]] is incorporated.\n*[[1916]] &ndash; United States President [[Woodrow Wilson]] sends 4,800 United States troops over the [[U.S.\u2013Mexico border]] to [[Pancho Villa Expedition|pursue Pancho Villa]].\n*[[1917]] &ndash; [[Tsar]] [[Nicholas II of Russia]] abdicates the Russian throne ending the 304-year Romanov dynasty.\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[Talaat Pasha]], former Grand Vizir of the [[Ottoman Empire]] and chief architect of the [[Armenian Genocide]] is assassinated in Berlin by a 23-year-old Armenian, Soghomon Tehlirian. \n*[[1922]] &ndash; After [[Egypt]] gains nominal independence from the United Kingdom, [[Fuad I of Egypt|Fuad I]] becomes [[King of Egypt]].\n*[[1926]] &ndash; The dictator [[Theodoros Pangalos (general)|Theodoros Pangalos]] is elected President of Greece without opposition.\n*[[1927]] &ndash; The first [[Women's Boat Race]] between the [[University of Oxford]] and the [[University of Cambridge]] takes place on [[The Isis]] in [[Oxford]].\n*[[1931]] &ndash; {{SS|Viking}} explodes off [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]], killing 27 of the 147 on board.\n*[[1933]] &ndash; Austrian Chancellor [[Engelbert Dollfuss]] keeps members of the [[National Council of Austria|National Council]] from convening, starting the [[Austrofascism|Austrofascist]] dictatorship.\n*[[1939]] &ndash; [[German occupation of Czechoslovakia|Germany occupies Czechoslovakia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radio.cz/en/section/czech-history/march-15-1939-the-day-czechoslovakia-ceased-to-exist|title=March 15, 1939 - The day Czechoslovakia ceased to exist|date=March 15, 2019|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n*  1939   &ndash; [[Carpatho-Ukraine]] declares itself an independent republic, but is annexed by Hungary the next day.\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[Philippine Airlines]], the flag carrier of the [[Philippines]] takes its first flight between [[Manila]] (from [[Nielson Field]]) to [[Baguio|Baguio City]] with a [[Beechcraft Model 18]] making the airline the first and oldest commercial airline in Asia operating under its original name.\n*[[1943]] &ndash; World War II: [[Third Battle of Kharkov]]: The Germans retake the city of [[Kharkov]] from the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] armies in bitter street fighting.\n*[[1945]] &ndash; World War II: Soviet forces begin an [[Upper Silesian Offensive|offensive]] to push Germans from [[Upper Silesia]].\n*[[1951]] &ndash; Iranian oil industry is [[Nationalization of the Iranian oil industry|nationalized]]. \n*[[1952]] &ndash; In [[Cilaos]], [[R\u00e9union]], 1870&nbsp;mm (73&nbsp;inches) of rain falls in a 24-hour period, setting a new world record (March 15 through March 16).\n*[[1961]] &ndash; At the [[1961 Commonwealth Prime Ministers' Conference]], South Africa announces that it will withdraw from the Commonwealth when the [[South African Constitution of 1961]] comes into effect.\n*[[1965]] &ndash; President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], responding to the [[Selma, Alabama|Selma]] crisis, tells [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] \"We shall overcome\" while advocating the [[Voting Rights Act]].\n*[[1978]] &ndash; [[Somalia]] and [[Ethiopia]] signed a truce to end the [[Ethio-Somali War]].\n*[[1986]] &ndash; [[Collapse of Hotel New World]]: Thirty-three people die when the Hotel New World in Singapore collapses.\n*[[1990]] &ndash; [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] is elected as the first [[President of the Soviet Union]].\n*[[1991]] &ndash; [[Cold War]]: The [[Treaty on the Final Settlement with Respect to Germany]] comes into effect, granting full sovereignty to the [[Germany|Federal Republic of Germany]].\n*[[2008]] &ndash; Stockpiles of obsolete ammunition [[2008 G\u00ebrdec explosions|explode]] at an ex-military ammunition depot in the village of [[G\u00ebrdec]], [[Albania]], killing 26 people. \n*[[2011]] &ndash; Beginning of the [[Syrian Civil War]].\n*[[2019]] &ndash; Fifty-one people are killed in the [[Christchurch mosque shootings]].\n*  2019   &ndash; Approximately 1.4 million young people in 123 countries go on strike to protest climate change.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/energy-and-environment/2019/3/15/18267156/youth-climate-strike-march-15-photos|title=Photos: kids in 123 countries went on strike to protect the climate|last1=Barclay|first1=Eliza|last2=Amaria|first2=Kainaz|publisher=Vox|date=March 17, 2019|accessdate=March 17, 2019}}</ref>\n<!-- Please do not add the SCIENTOLOGY event here without first discussing the event's notability to consensus on the talk page. -->\n\n==Births==\n* [[270]] &ndash; [[Saint Nicholas]], Greek bishop and saint (d. 343)\n*[[1097]] &ndash; [[Fujiwara no Tadamichi]], Japanese noble (d. 1164)\n*[[1275]] &ndash; [[Margaret of England, Duchess of Brabant]] (d. 1333)\n*[[1407]] &ndash; [[Jacob, Margrave of Baden-Baden]] (d. 1453)\n*[[1444]] &ndash; [[Francesco Gonzaga (1444\u20131483)|Francesco Gonzaga]], Catholic cardinal (d. 1483)\n*[[1493]] &ndash; [[Anne de Montmorency]], French captain and diplomat (d. 1567)<ref>{{cite book | last=Potter | first=David | title=A History of France, 1460-1560: the Emergence of a Nation State | publisher=St. Martin's Press | place=New York | year=1985 | isbn= 978-0-31212-480-9 | page=97}}</ref>\n*[[1513]] &ndash; [[Hedwig Jagiellon, Electress of Brandenburg]] (d. 1573)\n*[[1516]] &ndash; [[Alqas Mirza]], Safavid prince (d. 1550)<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | title = ALQ\u0100S M\u012aRZA | last = Fleischer | first = C. | authorlink = | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/alqas-alqasb-alqas-mirza-safawi | editor-last = | editor-first =  | editor-link = | encyclopedia  = Encyclopaedia Iranica, Vol. I, Fasc. 9 | pages = 907\u2013909 | location = | publisher = | year = 1989 | isbn = |ref=harv}}</ref>\n*[[1582]] &ndash; [[Daniel Featley]], English theologian and controversialist (d. 1645)\n*[[1584]] &ndash; [[Philip, Duke of Schleswig-Holstein-Sonderburg-Gl\u00fccksburg]] (d. 1663)\n*[[1591]] &ndash; [[Alexandre de Rhodes]], French missionary and lexicographer (d. 1660)\n*[[1611]] &ndash; [[Jan Fyt]], Flemish painter (d. 1661)\n*[[1638]] &ndash; [[Shunzhi Emperor]] of China (d. 1661)\n*[[1666]] &ndash; [[George B\u00e4hr]], German architect, designed the [[Dresden Frauenkirche]] (d. 1738)\n*[[1754]] &ndash; [[Archibald Menzies]], Scottish surgeon and botanist (d. 1842)\n*[[1767]] &ndash; [[Andrew Jackson]], American general, judge, and politician, 7th [[President of the United States]] (d. 1845)\n*[[1779]] &ndash; [[William Lamb, 2nd Viscount Melbourne]], English politician, [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (d. 1848)\n*[[1790]] &ndash; [[Ludwig Immanuel Magnus]], German mathematician and academic (d. 1861)<ref>{{cite book|author1=Isidore Singer|author2=Cyrus Adler|title=The Jewish Encyclopedia: Leon-Moravia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xlpLAQAAMAAJ|year=1904|publisher=Funk & Wagnalls|page=258}}</ref>\n*[[1791]] &ndash; [[Charles Knight (publisher)|Charles Knight]], English author and publisher (d. 1873)\n*[[1809]] &ndash; [[Joseph Jenkins Roberts]], American-Liberian historian and politician, 1st [[President of Liberia]] (d. 1876)\n*  1809   &ndash; [[Karl Josef von Hefele]], German bishop and theologian (d. 1893)\n*[[1813]] &ndash; [[John Snow]], English physician and epidemiologist (d. 1858)\n*[[1818]] &ndash; [[Mariano \u00c1lvarez]], Filipino general and politician (d. 1924)\n*[[1821]] &ndash; [[Johann Josef Loschmidt]], Austrian physicist and chemist (d. 1895)\n*  1821   &ndash; [[William Milligan]], Scottish theologian, author, and educator (d. 1892)\n*[[1824]] &ndash; [[Jules Chevalier]], French priest, founded the [[Missionaries of the Sacred Heart]] (d. 1907)\n*[[1830]] &ndash; [[Paul Heyse]], German author, poet, and playwright, [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1914)\n*  1830   &ndash; [[\u00c9lis\u00e9e Reclus]], French geographer and academic (d. 1905)\n*[[1831]] &ndash; [[Saint Daniele Comboni]], Italian missionary and saint (d. 1881)\n*[[1835]] &ndash; [[John Henry Kagi]], American lawyer and activist (d. 1859)\n*  1835   &ndash; [[Eduard Strauss]], Austrian composer and conductor (d. 1916)\n*[[1838]] &ndash; [[Karl Davydov]], Russian cellist, composer, and conductor (d. 1889)\n*[[1851]] &ndash; [[John Sebastian Little]], American lawyer and politician, 21st [[Governor of Arkansas]] (d. 1916)\n*  1851   &ndash; [[William Mitchell Ramsay]], Scottish archaeologist and scholar (d. 1939)\n*[[1852]] &ndash; [[Augusta, Lady Gregory]], Anglo-Irish landowner, playwright, and translator (d. 1932)\n*[[1854]] &ndash; [[Emil von Behring]], German physiologist and physician, [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1917)\n*[[1857]] &ndash; [[Christian Michelsen]], Norwegian businessman and politician, 1st [[Prime Minister of Norway]] (d. 1925)\n*[[1858]] &ndash; [[Liberty Hyde Bailey]], American botanist and academic, co-founded the [[American Society for Horticultural Science]] (d. 1954)\n*[[1860]] &ndash; [[Waldemar Haffkine]], Russian-Swiss bacteriologist and microbiologist (d. 1930)\n*[[1864]] &ndash; [[Johan Halvorsen]], Norwegian violinist, composer, and conductor ([[Oslo Philharmonic]]) (d. 1935)\n*[[1865]] &ndash; [[Manuk Abeghian]], Armenian author and scholar (d. 1944)\n*[[1866]] &ndash; [[Matthew Charlton]], Australian miner and politician (d. 1948)\n*  1866   &ndash; [[Johan Vaaler]], Norwegian inventor, often erroneously identified as the inventor of the [[Paper clip]] (d. 1910)\n*[[1868]] &ndash; [[Grace Chisholm Young]], English mathematician (d. 1944)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.agnesscott.edu/lriddle/women/young.htm|title=Grace Chisholm Young|publisher=[[Agnes Scott College]]|access-date=Dec 27, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[1869]] &ndash; [[Stanis\u0142aw Wojciechowski]], Polish scholar and politician, 2nd [[List of heads of state of Poland|President of the Republic of Poland]] (d. 1953)\n*[[1874]] &ndash; [[Eug\u00e8ne Fiset]], Canadian physician, general, and politician, 18th [[Lieutenant Governor of Quebec]] (d. 1951)\n*  1874   &ndash; [[Harold L. Ickes]], American journalist and politician, 32nd [[United States Secretary of the Interior]] (d. 1952)\n*[[1878]] &ndash; [[Reza Shah]], Iranian king (d. 1944)\n*[[1886]] &ndash; [[Wladimir Burliuk]], Ukrainian-Greek painter and illustrator (d. 1917)\n*[[1887]] &ndash; [[Marjorie Merriweather Post]], American businesswoman and philanthropist, founded [[General Foods]] (d. 1973)\n*  1887   &ndash; [[L\u00fctfi K\u0131rdar]], Turkish physician and politician, [[Ministry of Health (Turkey)|Turkish Minister of Health]] (d. 1961)\n*[[1879]] &ndash; [[Benjamin R. Jacobs]], American biochemist (d. 1963)<ref>''Announcements'', ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'', New Series, volume 139, number 3557, pp.&nbsp;818\u2013819, March 1963</ref>\n*[[1890]] &ndash; [[Boris Delaunay]], Russian mathematician and mountaineer (d. 1980)\n*[[1892]] &ndash; [[James Basevi Ord]], Mexican-American colonel (d. 1938)\n*[[1897]] &ndash; [[Jackson Scholz]], American runner (d. 1986)\n*[[1900]] &ndash; [[Gilberto Freyre]], Brazilian sociologist, anthropologist, historian and writer (d. 1987)\n*[[1904]] &ndash; [[George Brent]], Irish-American actor (d. 1979)\n*  1904   &ndash; [[J. Pat O'Malley]], English-American actor (d. 1985)\n*[[1905]] &ndash; [[Berthold Schenk Graf von Stauffenberg]], German lawyer and judge (d. 1944)\n*[[1907]] &ndash; [[Zarah Leander]], Swedish actress and singer (d. 1981)\n*[[1909]] &ndash; [[Jaroslava Muchov\u00e1|Jaroslava Muchov\u00e1 Syllabov\u00e1]], Czech painter (d. 1986)\n*[[1912]] &ndash; [[Lightnin' Hopkins]], American blues singer-songwriter and guitarist (d. 1982)\n*  1912   &ndash; [[Louis Paul Boon]], Flemish journalist and author (d. 1979)\n*[[1913]] &ndash; [[Macdonald Carey]], American actor (d. 1994)\n*  1913   &ndash; [[Jack Fairman]], English race car driver (d. 2002)\n*[[1916]] &ndash; [[Frank Coghlan, Jr.]], American actor and pilot (d. 2009)\n*  1916   &ndash; [[Fadil Hoxha]], Kosovar commander and politician, 2nd [[President of Kosovo]] (d. 2001)\n*  1916   &ndash; [[Harry James]], American trumpet player, bandleader, and actor (d. 1983)\n*[[1918]] &ndash; [[Richard Ellmann]], American author and critic (d. 1987)\n*  1918   &ndash; [[Punch Imlach]], Canadian ice hockey player, coach, and manager (d. 1987)\n*[[1919]] &ndash; [[Lawrence Tierney]], American actor (d. 2002)\n*[[1920]] &ndash; [[E. Donnall Thomas]], American physician and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2012)\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[Madelyn Pugh]], American television writer and producer (d. 2011)\n*[[1922]] &ndash; [[Eddie Calvert]], English trumpeter (d. 1978)\n*[[1926]] &ndash; [[Ben Johnston (composer)|Ben Johnston]], American composer and academic  (d. 2019)\n*  1926   &ndash; [[Norm Van Brocklin]], American football player and coach (d. 1983)\n*[[1927]] &ndash; [[Christian Marquand]], French actor, director, and screenwriter (d. 2000)\n*  1927   &ndash; [[Carl Smith (country musician)|Carl Smith]], American singer-songwriter and guitarist (d. 2010)\n*[[1928]] &ndash; [[Bob Wilber]], American clarinetist and saxophonist (d. 2019)\n*[[1930]] &ndash; [[Zhores Alferov]], Belarusian-Russian physicist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2019)<ref>{{cite book|author1=Benediktas Juodka|author2=V. P. Puronas|title=The Lithuanian Academy of Sciences|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CuYjAQAAIAAJ|year=2003|publisher=Lietuvos moksl\u0173 akademija|isbn=978-9986-08-038-1|page=169}}</ref>\n*[[1932]] &ndash; [[Alan Bea