enne]] (b. 1275)\n*  1311   &ndash; [[Thomas III d'Autremencourt]], Lord of Salona, Marshal of Achaea\n*  1311   &ndash; [[Albert Pallavicini]], Margrave of Bodonitza\n*  1311   &ndash; [[George I Ghisi]], Triarch of Euboea, Baron of Chalandritsa, Lord of Tinos, Mykonos, Serifos and Keos\n*[[1327]] &ndash; [[Albert of Schwarzburg]], grand preceptor of the Knights Hospitaller\n*[[1346]] &ndash; [[Shah Jalal]], Sufi saint of Bengal (b. 1271).\n*[[1536]] &ndash; [[Pargal\u0131 Ibrahim Pasha]], Ottoman politician, 35th [[List of Ottoman Grand Viziers|Grand Vizier of the Ottoman Empire]] (b. 1493)\n*[[1575]] &ndash; [[Annibale Padovano]], Italian organist and composer (b. 1527)\n*[[1644]] &ndash; [[Countess Louise Juliana of Nassau]] (b. 1576)\n*[[1657]] &ndash; [[David Pardo (Dutch rabbi, born at Salonica)|David Pardo]], Dutch rabbi and scholar (b. 1591)\n*[[1673]] &ndash; [[Salvator Rosa]], Italian painter and poet (b. 1615)\n*[[1711]] &ndash; [[Eusebio Kino]], Italian priest and missionary (b. 1645)\n*[[1820]] &ndash; [[Clement Mary Hofbauer]], Austrian priest and saint (b. 1751)\n*[[1832]] &ndash; [[Otto Wilhelm Masing]], Estonian linguist and clergyman (b. 1763)\n*[[1842]] &ndash; [[Luigi Cherubini]], Italian composer and theorist (b. 1760)\n*[[1849]] &ndash; [[Giuseppe Caspar Mezzofanti]], Italian cardinal and linguist (b. 1774)\n*[[1891]] &ndash; [[Joseph Bazalgette]], English engineer and academic (b. 1819)\n*[[1897]] &ndash; [[James Joseph Sylvester]], English mathematician and academic (b. 1814)\n*[[1898]] &ndash; [[Henry Bessemer]], English engineer and businessman (b. 1813)\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[Talaat Pasha]], Ottoman politician, 281st [[List of Ottoman Grand Viziers|Grand Vizier of the Ottoman Empire]] (b. 1874)\n*[[1927]] &ndash; [[Hector Rason]], English-Australian politician, 7th [[Premier of Western Australia]] (b. 1858)<ref>{{Dictionary of Australian Biography|First=Cornthwaite|Last=Rason|shortlink=0-dict-biogR.html#rason1}}</ref>\n*[[1933]] &ndash; [[Gustavo Jim\u00e9nez]], Peruvian colonel and politician, 73rd [[President of Peru]] (b. 1886)\n*[[1937]] &ndash; [[H. P. Lovecraft]], American short story writer, editor, and novelist (b. 1890)\n*[[1938]] &ndash; [[Nikolai Bukharin]], Russian journalist and politician (b. 1888)\n*[[1939]] &ndash; [[Luis Barcel\u00f3]], Spanish colonel (b. 1896)\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[Alexej von Jawlensky]], Russian-German painter (b. 1864)\n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[Otto von Below]], Prussian general (b. 1857)\n*[[1951]] &ndash; [[John S. Paraskevopoulos]], Greek-South African astronomer and academic (b. 1889)\n*[[1957]] &ndash; [[Ernst Nobs]], Swiss politician (b. 1886)\n*[[1959]] &ndash; [[Lester Young]], American saxophonist and clarinet player (b. 1909)\n*[[1962]] &ndash; [[Charles Bartliff]], American soccer player (b. 1886)\n*  1962   &ndash; [[Arthur Compton]], American physicist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1892)\n*[[1966]] &ndash; [[Abe Saperstein]], American basketball player and coach (b. 1902)\n*[[1969]] &ndash; [[Miles Malleson]], English actor and screenwriter (b. 1888)\n*  1969   &ndash; [[Musashiyama Takeshi]], Japanese sumo wrestler, the 33rd [[Makuuchi#Yokozuna|Yokozuna]] (b. 1909)\n*[[1970]] &ndash; [[Tarjei Vesaas]], Norwegian author and poet (b. 1897)\n*[[1971]] &ndash; [[Jean-Pierre Monser\u00e9]], Belgian cyclist (b. 1948)\n*[[1972]] &ndash; [[Aleksandr Ivanovich Laktionov]], Russian painter and educator (b. 1910)\n*[[1975]] &ndash; [[Aristotle Onassis]], Greek-Argentinian businessman (b. 1906)\n*[[1977]] &ndash; [[Hubert Aquin]], Canadian author and activist (b. 1929)\n*  1977   &ndash; [[Antonino Rocca]], Italian-American wrestler and referee (b. 1921)\n*[[1981]] &ndash; [[Ren\u00e9 Clair]], French director and screenwriter (b. 1898)\n*[[1983]] &ndash; [[Coloman Braun-Bogdan]], Romanian footballer and manager (b. 1905)\n*  1983   &ndash; [[Rebecca West]], English author and critic (b. 1892)\n*[[1985]] &ndash; [[Radha Krishna Choudhary]], Indian historian and author (b. 1921)\n*[[1986]] &ndash; [[Alexandru Giugaru]], Romanian actor (b. 1897)\n*[[1987]] &ndash; [[Douglas Abbott]], Canadian lawyer and politician, 10th [[Minister of National Defence (Canada)|Canadian Minister of National Defence]] (b. 1899)\n*[[1988]] &ndash; [[Dmitri Polyakov]], Ukrainian general and spy (b. 1926)\n*[[1989]] &ndash; [[Muhammad Jameel Didi]], Maldivian poet and politician (b. 1915)\n*[[1990]] &ndash; [[Farzad Bazoft]], Iranian-English journalist (b. 1958)\n*  1990   &ndash; [[Tom Harmon]], American football player and sportscaster (b. 1919)\n*[[1991]] &ndash; [[Bud Freeman]], American saxophonist, composer, and bandleader (b. 1906)\n*[[1992]] &ndash; [[Rahi Masoom Raza]], Indian [[Urdu]] poet (b.1927)\n*[[1997]] &ndash; [[Gail Davis]], American actress (b. 1925)\n*  1997   &ndash; [[Victor Vasarely]], Hungarian-French painter (b. 1906)\n*[[1998]] &ndash; [[Tim Maia]], Brazilian singer-songwriter (b. 1942)\n*  1998   &ndash; [[Benjamin Spock]], American pediatrician and author (b. 1903)\n*[[1999]] &ndash; [[Guy D'Artois]], Canadian soldier (b. 1917)\n*[[2001]] &ndash; [[Gaetano Cozzi]], Italian historian and academic (b. 1922)\n*  2001   &ndash; [[Ann Sothern]], American actress and singer (b. 1909)\n*[[2003]] &ndash; [[Thora Hird]], English actress (b. 1911)\n*  2003   &ndash; [[Paul Stojanovich]], American television producer, created ''[[World's Wildest Police Videos]]'' (b. 1956)\n*[[2004]] &ndash; [[Philippe Lemaire]], French actor (b. 1927)\n*  2004   &ndash; [[Bill Pickering (rocket scientist)|Bill Pickering]], New Zealand-American scientist and engineer (b. 1910)\n*  2004   &ndash; [[John Pople]], English-American chemist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1925)\n*[[2005]] &ndash; [[Bob Bellear]], Australian engineer and judge (b. 1944)\n*  2005   &ndash; [[Otar Korkia]], Georgian basketball player and coach (b. 1923)\n*  2005   &ndash; [[Shoji Nishio]], Japanese martial a