   &ndash; [[Booth Gardner]], American businessman and politician, 19th [[Governor of Washington]] (b. 1936)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Hardrock Gunter]], American singer-songwriter and guitarist (b. 1925)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Shannon Larratt]], Canadian publisher, founded ''[[BMEzine]]'' (b. 1973)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Terry Lightfoot]], English clarinet player (b. 1935)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Leverne McDonnell]], Australian actress (b. 1963).\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Masamichi Noro]], Japanese-French martial artist, founded [[Kinomichi]] (b. 1935)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Kallam Anji Reddy]], Indian engineer and businessman, founded [[Dr. Reddy's Laboratories]] (b. 1940)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Peter Worsley]], English sociologist (b. 1924)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Felipe Zetter]], Mexican footballer (b. 1923)\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[Scott Asheton]], American drummer (b. 1949).\n*  2014   &ndash; [[David Brenner]], American comedian, actor, and author (b. 1936)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Bo Callaway]], American soldier and politician, 11th [[United States Secretary of the Army]] (b. 1927)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Clarissa Dickson Wright]], English chef, author, and television personality (b. 1947)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Everett L. Fullam]], American priest and scholar (b. 1930)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Cees Veerman (musician)|Cees Veerman]], Dutch singer-songwriter and guitarist (b. 1943)\n*[[2015]] &ndash; [[Collins Chabane]], South African politician (b. 1960)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Robert Clatworthy (sculptor)|Robert Clatworthy]], English sculptor and educator (b. 1928)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Narayan Desai]], Indian author and activist (b. 1924)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Sally Forrest]], American actress and dancer (b. 1928)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Curtis Gans]], American political scientist and author (b. 1937)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Mike Porcaro]], American bass player (b. 1955)\n*[[2016]] &ndash; [[Sylvia Anderson]], English voice actress and television and film producer (b. 1927)\n*  2016   &ndash; [[Asa Briggs]], English historian and academic (b. 1921)\n*  2016   &ndash; [[Daryl Coley]], American singer and pastor (b. 1955)\n*  2016   &ndash; [[Seru Rabeni]], Fijian rugby player (b. 1978)\n*[[2019]] &ndash; [[Larry DiTillio]], American film and TV series writer (b. 1948)<ref>[https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/larry-ditillio-she-ra-he-man-obituary-j-michael-straczynski Larry DiTillio, co-creator of She-Ra and well-known genre TV writer has passed away], ''Syfy.com'' 17 March 2019. Accessed on 18 March 2019.</ref>\n*[[2020]] &ndash; [[Vittorio Gregotti]], Italian architect (b. 1927)<ref>{{cite news |last1=France-Presse |first1=Agence |title=Vittorio Gregotti, renowned Italian architect, dies of coronavirus at 92 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/vittorio-gregotti-renowned-italian-architect-dies-of-coronavirus-at-92?fbclid=IwAR1h4sC3GdqgAlPEKDcm1BoGEDquughXff1Xn6TdbfTHy6ohJABnFkvACQg |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n<!--Please do not add non-notable people, fictional characters, or people without Wikipedia articles to this list. No red links, please.\nDo not link multiple occurrences of the same year, just link the first occurrence. If there are multiple people in the same birth year, put them in alphabetical order. Do not trust \"this year in history\" websites for accurate date information.-->\n\n==Holidays and observances==\n*Christian [[feast day]]:\n**[[Aristobulus of Britannia]]\n**[[Clemens Maria Hofbauer]]\n**[[Martyrs of C\u00f3rdoba#Leocritia|Leocritia]]\n**[[Saint Longinus|Longinus]]\n**[[Louise de Marillac]]\n**[[Raymond of Fitero]]\n**[[March 15 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)]]\n*[[Constitution Day (Belarus)]]\n*Earliest day on which [[Fiestas Patrias (Mexico)|Birth of Benito Ju\u00e1rez]] can fall, while March 21 is the latest; celebrated on the third Monday of March. (Mexico)\n*Earliest day on which [[Palm Sunday]] can fall, while April 18 is the latest; celebrated on the sixth Sunday of [[Lent]]. ([[Christianity]])\n*[[H\u014dnen Matsuri]] ([[Japan]])\n*[[International Day Against Police Brutality]] ([[International observance|International]]) \n*[[J. J. Roberts' Birthday]] ([[Liberia]])\n*[[National Day (Hungary)|National Day]], celebrating the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1848]] (Hungary)\n*[[World Consumer Rights Day]] (International)\n*[[World Contact Day]]\n*[[World Day of Muslim Culture, Peace, Dialogue and Film]] (International)\n*[[World Speech Day]]\n*[[Youth Day (Palau)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/march/15 BBC: On This Day]\n*{{NYT On this day|month=03|day=15}}\n*[http://canadachannel.ca/todayincanadianhistory/index.php/March_15 Today in Canadian History]\n{{months}}\n\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:March]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\nIn the [[Roman calendar]], March 15 was known as the [[Ides of March]].\n\n==Events==\n*[[474 BC]] &ndash; [[Roman consul]] [[Gnaeus Manlius Vulso (consul 474 BC)|Gnaeus Manlius Vulso]] celebrates an [[ovation]] for concluding the [[Roman\u2013Etruscan Wars#Veii-Sabine alliance 475-474 BC|war]] against [[Veii]] and securing a forty years' truce.<ref>''[[Fasti Triumphales]]''</ref> \n*[[44 BC]] &ndash; [[Marcus Junius Brutus the Younger]] and his fellow conspirators, [[Gaius Cassius Longinus]], [[Decimus Junius Brutus Albinus|Decimus Junius Brutus]], and several other [[Roman Senate|Roman senators]], march to the Capitol following the [[assassination of Julius Caesar]], but there is no response to their appeals to the population, who have left the streets in fear. Caesar's body remains in its place \n* [[351]] &ndash; [[Constantius II]] elevates his cousin [[Constantius Gallus|Gallus]] to [[Caesar (title)|Caesar]], and puts him in charge of the Eastern part of the [[Roman Empire]].\n* [[493]] &ndash; [[Odoacer]], the first barbarian [[King of Italy]] after the fall of the [[Western Roman Empire]], is slain by [[Theoderic the Great]], king of the [[Ostrogoths]], while the two kings were feasting together.\n* [[856]] &ndash; [[Michael III]], emperor of the [[Byzantine Empire]], overthrows the regency of his mother, empress [[Theodora (wife of Theophilos)|Theodora]] (wife of Theophilos) with support of the Byzantine [[nobility]].\n* [[933]] &ndash; After a ten-year truce, German King [[Henry the Fowler]] defeats a Hungarian army at the [[Battle of Riade]] near the [[Unstrut]] river.\n*[[1147]] &ndash; [[Conquest of Santar\u00e9m]]: The forces of [[Afonso I of Portugal]] capture [[Santar\u00e9m, Portugal|Santar\u00e9m]].\n*[[1311]] &ndash; [[Battle of Halmyros]]: The [[Catalan Company]] defeats [[Walter V, Count of Brienne]] to take control of the [[Duchy of Athens]], a [[Crusader states|Crusader state]] in Greece.\n*[[1493]] &ndash; [[Christopher Columbus]] returns to Spain after his first trip to the Americas.\n*[[1564]] &ndash; Mughal Emperor [[Akbar]] abolishes \"[[jizya]]\" (''per capita'' tax).\n*[[1672]] &ndash; [[Charles II of England]] issues the [[Royal Declaration of Indulgence]].\n*[[1781]] &ndash; [[American Revolutionary War]]: [[Battle of Guilford Court House]]: Near present-day [[Greensboro, North Carolina]], 1,900 British troops under General [[Charles Cornwallis]] defeat a mixed American force numbering 4,400 in a [[Pyrrhic victory]].\n*[[1783]] &ndash; In an emotional speech in [[Newburgh, New York]], [[George Washington]] asks his officers not to support the [[Newburgh Conspiracy]]. The plea is successful and the threatened [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] never takes place.\n*[[1819]] &ndash; French physicist [[Augustin-Jean Fresnel|Augustin Fresnel]] is adjudged the winner of the ''Grand Prix'' of the [[French Academy of Sciences|Acad\u00e9mie des Sciences]] for his \"Memoir on the Diffraction of Light\", which verifies the [[Fresnel integral]]s, accounts for the limited extent to which light spreads into shadows, and thereby demolishes [[Isaac Newton|Newton]]'s initial objection to the wave theory of light.\n*[[1820]] &ndash; [[Maine]] becomes the 23rd [[U.S. state]].\n*[[1827]] &ndash; [[University of Toronto]] is founded.\n*[[1848]] &ndash; A [[Hungarian Revolution of 1848|revolution breaks out in Hungary]]. The [[Habsburg]] rulers are compelled to meet the demands of the Reform party.\n*[[1864]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: The [[Red River Campaign]]: U.S. Navy fleet arrives at [[Alexandria, Louisiana]].\n*[[1874]] &ndash; [[French Third Republic|France]] and [[Nguy\u1ec5n dynasty|Vietnam]] sign the [[Second Treaty of Saigon]], further recognizing the full sovereignty of France over [[Cochinchina]].\n*[[1875]] &ndash; [[Archbishop of New York]] [[John McCloskey]] is named the first [[cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]] in the United States.\n*[[1877]] &ndash; [[First ever official cricket test match is played]]: Australia vs England at the [[MCG Stadium]], in [[Melbourne]], Australia.\n*[[1878]] &ndash; [[Restoration of the Scottish Catholic hierarchy]], broken off back in 1603.\n*[[1888]] &ndash; Start of the [[Sikkim Expedition|Anglo-Tibetan War of 1888]].\n*[[1895]] &ndash; [[Heian Shrine]] is founded.\n*[[1906]] &ndash; [[Rolls-Royce Limited]] is incorporated.\n*[[1916]] &ndash; United States President [[Woodrow Wilson]] sends 4,800 United States troops over the [[U.S.\u2013Mexico border]] to [[Pancho Villa Expedition|pursue Pancho Villa]].\n*[[1917]] &ndash; [[Tsar]] [[Nicholas II of Russia]] abdicates the Russian throne ending the 304-year Romanov dynasty.\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[Talaat Pasha]], former Grand Vizir of the [[Ottoman Empire]] and chief architect of the [[Armenian Genocide]] is assassinated in Berlin by a 23-year-old Armenian, Soghomon Tehlirian. \n*[[1922]] &ndash; After [[Egypt]] gains nominal independence from the United Kingdom, [[Fuad I of Egypt|Fuad I]] becomes [[King of Egypt]].\n*[[1926]] &ndash; The dictator [[Theodoros Pangalos (general)|Theodoros Pangalos]] is elected President of Greece without opposition.\n*[[1927]] &ndash; The first [[Women's Boat Race]] between the [[University of Oxford]] and the [[University of Cambridge]] takes place on [[The Isis]] in [[Oxford]].\n*[[1931]] &ndash; {{SS|Viking}} explodes off [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]], killing 27 of the 147 on board.\n*[[1933]] &ndash; Austrian Chancellor [[Engelbert Dollfuss]] keeps members of the [[National Council of Austria|National Council]] from convening, starting the [[Austrofascism|Austrofascist]] dictatorship.\n*[[1939]] &ndash; [[German occupation of Czechoslovakia|Germany occupies Czechoslovakia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radio.cz/en/section/czech-history/march-15-1939-the-day-czechoslovakia-ceased-to-exist|title=March 15, 1939 - The day Czechoslovakia ceased to exist|date=March 15, 2019|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[1939]] &ndash; [[Carpatho-Ukraine]] declares itself an independent republic, but is annexed by Hungary the next day.\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[Philippine Airlines]], the flag carrier of the [[Philippines]] takes its first flight between [[Manila]] (from [[Nielson Field]]) to [[Baguio|Baguio City]] with a [[Beechcraft Model 18]] making the airline the first and oldest commercial airline in Asia operating under its original name.\n*[[1943]] &ndash; World War II: [[Third Battle of Kharkov]]: The Germans retake the city of [[Kharkov]] from the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] armies in bitter street fighting.\n*[[1945]] &ndash; World War II: Soviet forces begin an [[Upper Silesian Offensive|offensive]] to push Germans from [[Upper Silesia]].\n*[[1951]] &ndash; Iranian oil industry is [[Nationalization of the Iranian oil industry|nationalized]]. \n*[[1952]] &ndash; In [[Cilaos]], [[R\u00e9union]], 1870&nbsp;mm (73&nbsp;inches) of rain falls in a 24-hour period, setting a new world record (March 15 through March 16).\n*[[1961]] &ndash; At the [[1961 Commonwealth Prime Ministers' Conference]], South Africa announces that it will withdraw from the Commonwealth when the [[South African Constitution of 1961]] comes into effect.\n*[[1965]] &ndash; President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], responding to the [[Selma, Alabama|Selma]] crisis, tells [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] \"We shall overcome\" while advocating the [[Voting Rights Act]].\n*[[1978]] &ndash; [[Somalia]] and [[Ethiopia]] signed a truce to end the [[Ethio-Somali War]].\n*[[1986]] &ndash; [[Collapse of Hotel New World]]: Thirty-three people die when the Hotel New World in Singapore collapses.\n*[[1990]] &ndash; [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] is elected as the first [[President of the Soviet Union]].\n*[[1991]] &ndash; [[Cold War]]: The [[Treaty on the Final Settlement with Respect to Germany]] comes into effect, granting full sovereignty to the [[Germany|Federal Republic of Germany]].\n*[[2008]] &ndash; Stockpiles of obsolete ammunition [[2008 G\u00ebrdec explosions|explode]] at an ex-military ammunition depot in the village of [[G\u00ebrdec]], [[Albania]], killing 26 people. \n*[[2011]] &ndash; Beginning of the [[Syrian Civil War]].\n*[[2019]] &ndash; Fifty-one people are killed in the [[Christchurch mosque shootings]].\n*  2019   &ndash; Approximately 1.4 million young people in 123 countries go on strike to protest climate change.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/energy-and-environment/2019/3/15/18267156/youth-climate-strike-march-15-photos|title=Photos: kids in 123 countries went on strike to protect the climate|last1=Barclay|first1=Eliza|last2=Amaria|first2=Kainaz|publisher=Vox|date=March 17, 2019|accessdate=March 17, 2019}}</ref>\n<!-- Please do not add the SCIENTOLOGY event here without first discussing the event's notability to consensus on the talk page. -->\n\n==Births==\n* [[270]] &ndash; [[Saint Nicholas]], Greek bishop and saint (d. 343)\n*[[1097]] &ndash; [[Fujiwara no Tadamichi]], Japanese noble (d. 1164)\n*[[1275]] &ndash; [[Margaret of England, Duchess of Brabant]] (d. 1333)\n*[[1407]] &ndash; [[Jacob, Margrave of Baden-Baden]] (d. 1453)\n*[[1444]] &ndash; [[Francesco Gonzaga (1444\u20131483)|Francesco Gonzaga]], Catholic cardinal (d. 1483)\n*[[1493]] &ndash; [[Anne de Montmorency]], French captain and diplomat (d. 1567)<ref>{{cite book | last=Potter | first=David | title=A History of France, 1460-1560: the Emergence of a Nation State | publisher=St. Martin's Press | place=New York | year=1985 | isbn= 978-0-31212-480-9 | page=97}}</ref>\n*[[1513]] &ndash; [[Hedwig Jagiellon, Electress of Brandenburg]] (d. 1573)\n*[[1516]] &ndash; [[Alqas Mirza]], Safavid prince (d. 1550)<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | title = ALQ\u0100S M\u012aRZA | last = Fleischer | first = C. | authorlink = | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/alqas-alqasb-alqas-mirza-safawi | editor-last = | editor-first =  | editor-link = | encyclopedia  = Encyclopaedia Iranica, Vol. I, Fasc. 9 | pages = 907\u2013909 | location = | publisher = | year = 1989 | isbn = |ref=harv}}</ref>\n*[[1582]] &ndash; [[Daniel Featley]], English theologian and controversialist (d. 1645)\n*[[1584]] &ndash; [[Philip, Duke of Schleswig-Holstein-Sonderburg-Gl\u00fccksburg]] (d. 1663)\n*[[1591]] &ndash; [[Alexandre de Rhodes]], French missionary and lexicographer (d. 1660)\n*[[1611]] &ndash; [[Jan Fyt]], Flemish painter (d. 1661)\n*[[1638]] &ndash; [[Shunzhi Emperor]] of China (d. 1661)\n*[[1666]] &ndash; [[George B\u00e4hr]], German architect, designed the [[Dresden Frauenkirche]] (d. 1738)\n*[[1754]] &ndash; [[Archibald Menzies]], Scottish surgeon and botanist (d. 1842)\n*[[1767]] &ndash; [[Andrew Jackson]], American general, judge, and politician, 7th [[President of the United States]] (d. 1845)\n*[[1779]] &ndash; [[William Lamb, 2nd Viscount Melbourne]], English politician, [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (d. 1848)\n*[[1790]] &ndash; [[Ludwig Immanuel Magnus]], German mathematician and academic (d. 1861)<ref>{{cite book|author1=Isidore Singer|author2=Cyrus Adler|title=The Jewish Encyclopedia: Leon-Moravia|